            "content": [
              {
                "type": "output_text",
                "text": "This place—**Centralia, Pennsylvania**—is special because it’s a **near–ghost town created by an underground coal-mine fire that has been burning since May 1962**. The fire led to dangerous ground instability (collapse), toxic gases, and widespread evacuation; the state eventually condemned most property and the population fell to just a handful of residents. ([pa.gov](https://www.pa.gov/agencies/dep/programs-and-services/mining/abandoned-mine-reclamation/aml-program-information/centralia-mine-fire-resources))\n\nOther notable “Centralia” specifics people associate with it:\n\n- **ZIP code 17927 was discontinued (2002)** due to the tiny remaining population, with mail shifted to nearby Ashland’s ZIP. ([en.wikipedia.org](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Centralia%2C_Pennsylvania))  \n- The infamous abandoned stretch of **PA Route 61 (“Graffiti Highway”)** became a tourist/graffiti site, but it was **buried/blocked in 2020** to deter visits. ([atlasobscura.com](https://www.atlasobscura.com/articles/centralia-graffiti-highway-buried))  \n- Pennsylvania DEP warns the immediate area can be **dangerous to visit** due to gas and sudden ground collapse. ([pa.gov](https://www.pa.gov/agencies/dep/programs-and-services/mining/abandoned-mine-reclamation/aml-program-information/centralia-mine-fire-resources))",
